===={{IPA|/ɪø, ɪə, ʊə/}}====
* According to {{Harvcoltxt|Lass|1987}}, the first elements of {{IPA|[ɪø, ɪə, ʊə]}} are close-mid,{{sfnp|Lass|1987|pp=117–119}} more narrowly transcribed {{IPA|[ë, ë, ö]}} or {{IPA|[ɪ̞, ɪ̞, ʊ̞]}}. According to {{Harvcoltxt|De Villiers|1976}}, the onsets of {{IPA|[ɪə, ʊə]}} are near-close {{IPA|[ɪ, ʊ]}}.{{sfnp|De Villiers|1976|pp=56–57}} For simplicity, both variants will be written simply as {{IPA|[ɪø, ɪə, ʊə]}}. {{IPA|[ɪ, ʊ]}} are commonly used for centralized close-mid vowels anyway - see [[near-close near-front unrounded vowel]] and [[near-close near-back rounded vowel]].
* Some sources prescribe monophthongal {{IPA|[{{IPA link|øː}}, {{IPA link|eː}}, {{IPA link|oː}}]}} realizations of these; that is at least partially outdated:{{sfnp|Lass|1987|pp=117–119}}{{sfnp|Donaldson|1993|p=8}}
** There is not a complete agreement about the realisation of {{IPA|/ɪø/}}:
*** According to {{Harvcoltxt|Lass|1987}}, it is realised as either rising {{IPA|[ɪ̯ø]}} or falling {{IPA|[ɪø̯]}}, with the former being more common. The unrounded onset is a rather recent development and is not described by older sources. The monophthongal realisation {{IPAblink|øː}} is virtually nonexistent.{{sfnp|Lass|1987|p=117}}
*** According to {{Harvcoltxt|Donaldson|1993}}, it is realised as {{IPA|[øə]}}. Its onset is sometimes unrounded, which can cause it to merge with {{IPA|/eə/}}.{{sfnp|Donaldson|1993|pp=8–9}}
** There is not a complete agreement about the realisation of {{IPA|/ɪə, ʊə/}}
*** According to {{Harvcoltxt|Lass|1987}}, they may be realised in four ways:
**** Falling diphthongs. Their first element may be short {{IPA|[ɪə̯, ʊə̯]}} or somewhat lengthened {{IPA|[ɪˑə̯, ʊˑə̯]}}.{{sfnp|Lass|1987|pp=117–119}}
**** Rising diphthongs {{IPA|[ɪ̯ə, ʊ̯ə]}}. These variants do not seem to appear word-finally. The sequence {{IPA|/ɦʊə/}} is commonly realised as {{IPA|[ɦʊ̯ə]}} or, more often, {{IPA|[ɦʊ̯ə̤]}}, with {{IPA|/ɦ/}} realised as [[breathy voice]] on the diphthong.{{sfnp|Lass|1987|pp=117–119}}
**** Indeterminate diphthongs {{IPA|[ɪə, ʊə]}}, which may occur in all environments.{{sfnp|Lass|1987|pp=117–119}}
**** Monophthongs, either short {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɪ}}, {{IPA link|ʊ}}]}} or somewhat lengthened {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɪˑ}}, {{IPA link|ʊˑ}}]}}. The monophthongal realisations occur in less stressed words as well as in stressed syllables in words that have more than one syllable. In the latter case, they are in free variation with all of the three diphthongal realisations. In case of {{IPA|/ʊə/}}, the monophthongal {{IPAblink|ʊ}} also appears in unstressed word-final syllables.{{sfnp|Lass|1987|pp=117–119}}
*** According to {{Harvcoltxt|Donaldson|1993}}, they are realized as either {{IPA|[eə, oə]}} or {{IPA|[iə, uə]}}.{{sfnp|Donaldson|1993|p=8}}
* {{IPA|/ɪə/}} also occurs in words spelled with {{angle bracket|eë}}, like ''reël'' {{IPA|/ˈrɪəl/}} 'rule'. Historically, these were pronounced with a disyllabic sequence {{IPA|/eː.ə/}} and so ''reël'' used to be pronounced {{IPA|/ˈreː.əl/}}.{{sfnp|Donaldson|1993|p=8}}
* There is not a complete agreement about the dialectal realisation of {{IPA|/ɪə, ʊə/}} in the [[Boland, Western Cape|Boland]] area:
** According to {{Harvcoltxt|Lass|1987}}, they are centralized close-mid monophthongs {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɪ}}, {{IPA link|ʊ}}]}}, which do not merge with {{IPA|/i/}} and {{IPA|/u/}}.{{sfnp|Lass|1987|p=118}}
** According to {{Harvcoltxt|Donaldson|1993}} and De Villiers,<ref name="dv">Cited in {{Harvcoltxt|Lass|1987|pp=117–118}}. The preview on Google Books makes it unclear whether De Villiers' book is "Afrikaanse klankleer. Fonetiek, fonologie en woordbou" or "Nederlands en Afrikaans", as both are cited at the end of Lass's chapter.</ref> they are close monophthongs, long {{IPA|[{{IPA link|iː}}, {{IPA link|uː}}]}} according to {{Harvcoltxt|Donaldson|1993}}, short {{IPA|[{{IPA link|i}}, {{IPA link|u}}]}} according to De Villiers.{{sfnp|Donaldson|1993|p=8}}<ref name="dv"/>

====Other diphthongs====
* The scholar Daan Wissing argues that {{IPA|/əi/}} is not a phonetically correct transcription and that {{IPA|/æɛ/}} is more accurate. In his analysis, he found that {{IPA|[æɛ]}} makes for 65% of the realisations, the other 35% being monophthongal, {{IPAblink|ə}}, {{IPAblink|æ}} and {{IPAblink|ɛ}}.{{sfnp|Wissing|2009|p=333}}
* Most often, {{IPA|/œi/}} has an unrounded offset. For some speakers, the onset is also unrounded. That can cause {{IPA|/œi/}} to merge with {{IPA|/əi/}}, which is considered non-standard.{{sfnp|Donaldson|1993|p=10}}
* {{IPA|/ɔi, ai/}} occur mainly in loanwords.{{sfnp|Donaldson|1993|p=10}}
* Older sources describe {{IPA|/œu/}} as a narrow back diphthong {{IPA|[ou]}}.{{sfnp|Donaldson|1993|p=9}}{{sfnp|Swanepoel|1927|p=44}} However, newer sources describe its onset as more front. For example, {{Harvcoltxt|Lass|1984}}, states that the onset of {{IPA|/œu/}} is central {{IPA|[ɵu]}}.{{sfnp|Lass|1984|p=102}}
** In some words, which, in English, are pronounced with {{IPA|/əʊ/}}, the Afrikaans equivalent tends to be pronounced with {{IPA|/œu/}}, rather than {{IPA|/ʊə/}}. That happens because Afrikaans {{IPA|/œu/}} is more similar to the usual South African realization of English {{IPA|/əʊ/}}.{{sfnp|Donaldson|1993|p=9}}

