====Long diphthongs====
The long diphthongs (or 'double vowels') are phonemically sequences of a free vowel and a non-syllabic equivalent of {{IPA|/i/}} or {{IPA|/u/}}: {{IPA|[iu, ui, oːi, eu, ɑːi]}}. Both {{IPA|[iu]}} and {{IPA|[eu]}} tend to be pronounced as {{IPA|[iu]}}, but they are spelled differently: the former as {{angle bracket|ieu}}, the latter as {{angle bracket|eeu}}.{{sfnp|Donaldson|1993|p=12}}

===='False' diphthongs====
In diminutives ending in {{IPA|/ki/}} formed to monosyllabic nouns, the vowels {{IPA|/u, ɪə, ʊə, ɛ, ə, œ, ɔ, a, ɑː/}} are realised as closing diphthongs {{IPA|[ui, ei, oi, ɛi, əi, œi, ɔi, ai, ɑːi]}}. In the same environment, the sequences {{IPA|/ɛn, ən, œn, ɔn, an/}} are realized as {{IPA|[ɛiɲ, əiɲ, œiɲ, ɔiɲ, aiɲ]}}, i.e. as closing diphthongs followed by palatal nasal.{{sfnp|Donaldson|1993|pp=10–11}}

* The suffixes {{angle bracket|-aad}} and {{angle bracket|-aat}} (phonemically {{IPA|/ɑːd/}} and {{IPA|/ɑːt/}}, respectively) and the diminutive suffix {{IPA|/ki/}} are realised as {{IPA|[ɑːci]}} (with a monophthong), rather than {{IPA|[ɑːici]}}.{{sfnp|Donaldson|1993|p=10}}
* In practice, the diphthong {{IPA|[əi]}} is realised the same as the phonemic diphthong {{IPA|/əi/}}.{{sfnp|Donaldson|1993|p=11}}
* {{IPA|[œi]}}, when it has arisen from diphthongisation of {{IPA|[œ]}}, differs from the phonemic diphthong {{IPA|/œi/}} by having a slightly different onset, although the exact nature of that difference is unclear. This means that ''puntjie'' 'point' sounds somewhat different than ''puintjie'' 'rubble'.{{sfnp|Donaldson|1993|p=11}}

