===Obstruents===
* All obstruents at the ends of words are [[final-obstruent devoicing|devoiced]] so that, for instance, a final {{IPA|/d/}} is realised as {{IPA|[t]}}.{{sfnp|Donaldson|1993|pp=13–15}}
* {{IPA|/p, b/}} are [[Bilabial consonant|bilabial]], whereas {{IPA|/f, v/}} are [[Labiodental consonant|labiodental]].
** According to some authors,<ref>For example {{Harvcoltxt|Den Besten|2012}}.</ref> {{IPA|/v/}} is actually an approximant {{IPAblink|ʋ}}.
* {{IPA|/p, t, k, tʃ/}} are unaspirated.{{sfnp|Donaldson|1993|pp=14–16}}
* {{IPA|/k/}} may be somewhat more front before front vowels; the fronted allophone of {{IPA|/k/}} also occurs in diminutives ending in ''-djie'' and ''-tjie''.{{sfnp|Donaldson|1993|p=15}}
* {{IPA|/dʒ, z/}} occur only in loanwords.
* {{IPA|/χ/}} is most often uvular, either a fricative, {{IPAblink|χ}} or a voiceless trill {{IPAblink|ʀ̥}}, the latter especially in initial position before a stressed vowel.{{sfnp|Den Besten|2012}}<ref name="wellsblog">{{cite web|title=John Wells's phonetic blog: velar or uvular?|url=http://phonetic-blog.blogspot.com/2011/12/velar-or-uvular.html|date=5 December 2011|accessdate=12 February 2015}} Only this source mentions the trilled realization.</ref><ref name="bowerman">{{Harvcoltxt|Bowerman|2004|p=939}}: "White South African English is one of very few varieties to have a velar fricative phoneme {{IPA|/x/}} (see {{Harvcoltxt|Lass|2002|p=120}}), but this is only in words borrowed from Afrikaans (...) and [[Khoisan languages|Khoisan]] (...). Many speakers use the Afrikaans uvular fricative {{IPA|[χ]}} rather than the velar."</ref> The uvular fricative is also used by many speakers of White [[South African English]] as a realisation of the marginal English phoneme {{IPA|/x/}}.<ref name="bowerman"/> In Afrikaans, velar {{IPAblink|x}} may be used in a few "hyper-posh" varieties, and it may also, rarely, occur as an allophone before front vowels in speakers with otherwise uvular {{IPAblink|χ}}.<ref name="wellsblog"/>
* {{IPA|/ɡ/}} occurs only in loanwords. In some environments,{{fix|text=which?|date=July 2015}} {{IPA|[ɡ]}} is an allophone of {{IPA|/χ/}}.{{sfnp|Donaldson|1993|pp=13–14}}

===Sonorants===
* {{IPA|/m/}} is [[Bilabial consonant|bilabial]].
* {{IPA|/n/}} merges with {{IPA|/m/}} before labial consonants. Phonetically, this merged consonant is realized as bilabial {{IPA|[m]}} before {{IPA|/p, b/}}, and labiodental {{IPA|[ɱ]}} before {{IPA|/f, v/}}.
** {{IPA|/n/}} merges with {{IPA|/ŋ/}} before dorsals ({{IPA|/k, χ/}}). Phonetically, this merged consonant is realized as velar {{IPAblink|ŋ}} before {{IPA|/k/}} and the {{IPA|[ɡ]}} allophone of {{IPA|/χ/}},{{fix|text=can {{IPA|[ɡ]}} occur after {{IPA|[ŋ]}}?|date=May 2015}} and as uvular {{IPAblink|ɴ}} before {{IPA|/χ/}}.
* {{IPA|/l/}} is [[Velarisation|velarised]] {{IPAblink|ɫ}} in all positions, especially noticeably non-prevocalically.{{sfnp|Lass|1987|p=117}}{{sfnp|Donaldson|1993|p=15}}
* {{IPA|/r/}} is usually an alveolar trill {{IPAblink|r}} or tap {{IPAblink|ɾ}}.{{sfnp|Lass|1987|p=117}} In some parts of the former [[Cape Province]], it is realised uvularly, either as a trill {{IPAblink|ʀ}} or a fricative {{IPAblink|ʁ}}.{{sfnp|Donaldson|1993|p=15}} The uvular trill may also be pronounced as a tap {{IPAblink|ʀ̆}}.

