'''Prison of the peoples''' ({{lang-ru|Тюрьма́ наро́дов}}) is a [[phrase]] first used by [[Vladimir Lenin]] in 1914. He applied it to [[Russian Empire]], describing the national policy of that time.<ref>{{cite book |last=Brandenberger |first=David |date=2002 |title=National Bolshevism: Stalinist Mass Culture and the Formation of Modern Russian National Identity, 1931-1956 |url= |location= |publisher=Harvard University Press |page= |isbn=9780674009066 |author-link= }}</ref> The idea of calling Russia a prison is based on [[Marquis de Custine]]'s book ''[[La Russie en 1839]]''.

