{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}} {{Use Indian English|date=June 2018}} {{Infobox writer | name = Sathankulam. M. Abdul Jabbar | image = | caption = | birth_name = M. Abdul Jabbar | birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1939|6|26}} | birth_place = [[Sathankulam]], [[Tamil Nadu]] | occupation = Media personality, writer | language = [[Tamil language|Tamil]] | nationality = [[India]]n | period = 1951 - ''present'' | subject = Literature, philosophy, religion, sports | notableworks = | website = | spouse = | children = }}
'''S. M. Abdul Jabbar''' (born June 26, 1939, Sathankulam, Tamil Nadu) is a [[Tamil language|Tamil]] radio broadcaster, cricket commentator, writer and actor.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.viruba.com/atotalbooks.aspx?id=334|title=காற்று வெளியினிலே|accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref>
==Early life== S. M. Abdul Jabbar was born into a middle class Muslim family and grew up in the small town of [[Sathankulam]], presently in [[Thoothukudi district]] in the state of [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]]. Having relatives in [[Sri Lanka]], he relocated to [[Colombo]] for his higher studies. After completing his education he moved back to India due to the tense [[Sri Lankan Tamil nationalism|political situation]] in Sri Lanka.
== Radio and cricket commentary == Born in the [[Golden Age of Radio]], Jabbar became a regular radio listener during his childhood in India and Sri Lanka. He often wrote letters to radio stations about their programs. On one occasion, he wrote a letter to [[All India Radio]] that was critical of its [[Tamil language]] cricket commentary. The letter was read on air, and he was invited to show his skill by providing Tamil commentary of the [[Ranji Trophy]] match between [[Tamil Nadu]] and [[Kerala]]. The opportunity changed his life.
Abdul Jabbar already had considerable experience anchoring Tamil programs for the [[Sri Lanka Broadcasting Corporation]] when he joined the AIR [[Chennai]] Tamil commentary team in 1979.<ref name="WI"/> He learned substantially from commentating with Tamil radio pioneer and cricket writer V Ramamurthy. The AIR Tamil commentary team covered every [[Test cricket|test match]] and [[one day international]] played in Chennai, and many of the regional matches. Jabbar's commentary remained popular through the 1990s,<ref>{{cite news|work=The Indian Express|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/sports/cricket/in-search-of-the-beginnings-of-chepauks-walajah-road-end-4850065/|access-date=4 July 2018|date=19 September 2017|title=India vs Australia: In search of beginnings of Chepauk’s Walajah Road End|first=Sandip|last=G}}</ref> with a fan base in Tamil Nadu and Sri Lanka that included [[LTTE]] supremo [[Velupillai Prabhakaran]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/yourlanguage/tamil/en/audiotrack/prabhakarans-appreciation-was-best-award-received-life|title=Prabhakaran’s appreciation was the best award received in life|accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref> whom he interviewed in 2002.<ref>{{cite book|chapter=Tamil Muslims and the Dravidian Movement: Alliance and Contradictions|first=S|last=Anwar|title=Frontiers of Embedded Muslim Communities in India|isbn=9781136196805|location=London|publisher=Routledge India|pages=199–200|year=2011|editor-first=Vinod K.|editor-last=Jairath}}</ref> The AIR Tamil commentary team was disbanded in 2004, after which Abdul Jabbar continued providing Tamil commentary for the [[television channels]] [[ESPN]], [[Neo Sports]], [[Sun TV (India)|Sun TV]] and [[Zee TV|Zee]].<ref name="WI">{{cite web|url=https://www.wisdenindia.com/almanack-2015/languages-cricket-english-effect/179416|title=Languages of cricket – The English effect|publisher=Wisden India|access-date=4 July 2018|date=10 September 2015|first=Badri|last=Seshadri}}</ref>
